66def _make_comparison_op(op, cls): 

67 def cmp_method(self, other): 

68 if isinstance(other, (np.ndarray, Index, ABCSeries)): 

69 if other.ndim > 0 and len(self) != len(other): 

70 raise ValueError('Lengths must match to compare') 

71 

72 if is_object_dtype(self) and not isinstance(self, ABCMultiIndex): 

73 # don't pass MultiIndex 

74 with np.errstate(all='ignore'): 

75 result = ops._comp_method_OBJECT_ARRAY(op, self.values, other) 

76 

77 else: 

78 

79 # numpy will show a DeprecationWarning on invalid elementwise 

80 # comparisons, this will raise in the future 

81 with warnings.catch_warnings(record=True): 

82 warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", "elementwise", FutureWarning) 

83 with np.errstate(all='ignore'): 

84 result = op(self.values, np.asarray(other)) 

85 

86 # technically we could support bool dtyped Index 

87 # for now just return the indexing array directly 

88 if is_bool_dtype(result): 

89 return result 

90 try: 

91 return Index(result) 

92 except TypeError: 

93 return result

95 name = '__{name}__'.format(name=op.__name__)

97 return set_function_name(cmp_method, name, cls)

100def _make_arithmetic_op(op, cls): 

101 def index_arithmetic_method(self, other): 

102 if isinstance(other, (ABCSeries, ABCDataFrame)): 

103 return NotImplemented 

104 elif isinstance(other, ABCTimedeltaIndex): 

105 # Defer to subclass implementation 

106 return NotImplemented 

107 elif (isinstance(other, (np.ndarray, ABCTimedeltaArray)) and 

108 is_timedelta64_dtype(other)): 

109 # GH#22390; wrap in Series for op, this will in turn wrap in 

110 # TimedeltaIndex, but will correctly raise TypeError instead of 

111 # NullFrequencyError for add/sub ops 

112 from pandas import Series 

113 other = Series(other) 

114 out = op(self, other) 

115 return Index(out, name=self.name) 

116 

117 other = self._validate_for_numeric_binop(other, op) 

118 

119 # handle time-based others 

120 if isinstance(other, (ABCDateOffset, np.timedelta64, timedelta)): 

121 return self._evaluate_with_timedelta_like(other, op) 

122 elif isinstance(other, (datetime, np.datetime64)): 

123 return self._evaluate_with_datetime_like(other, op) 

124 

125 values = self.values 

126 with np.errstate(all='ignore'): 

127 result = op(values, other) 

128 

129 result = missing.dispatch_missing(op, values, other, result)

131 attrs = self._get_attributes_dict() 

132 attrs = self._maybe_update_attributes(attrs) 

133 if op is divmod: 

134 result = (Index(result[0], **attrs), Index(result[1], **attrs)) 

135 else: 

136 result = Index(result, **attrs) 

137 return result

165class Index(IndexOpsMixin, PandasObject): 

166 """ 

167 Immutable ndarray implementing an ordered, sliceable set. The basic object 

168 storing axis labels for all pandas objects. 

169 

170 Parameters 

171 ---------- 

172 data : array-like (1-dimensional) 

173 dtype : NumPy dtype (default: object) 

174 If dtype is None, we find the dtype that best fits the data. 

175 If an actual dtype is provided, we coerce to that dtype if it's safe. 

176 Otherwise, an error will be raised. 

177 copy : bool 

178 Make a copy of input ndarray 

179 name : object 

180 Name to be stored in the index 

181 tupleize_cols : bool (default: True) 

182 When True, attempt to create a MultiIndex if possible 

183 

184 See Also 

185 --------- 

186 RangeIndex : Index implementing a monotonic integer range. 

187 CategoricalIndex : Index of :class:`Categorical` s. 

188 MultiIndex : A multi-level, or hierarchical, Index. 

189 IntervalIndex : An Index of :class:`Interval` s. 

190 DatetimeIndex, TimedeltaIndex, PeriodIndex 

191 Int64Index, UInt64Index, Float64Index 

192 

193 Notes 

194 ----- 

195 An Index instance can **only** contain hashable objects 

196 

197 Examples 

198 -------- 

199 >>> pd.Index([1, 2, 3]) 

200 Int64Index([1, 2, 3], dtype='int64') 

201 

202 >>> pd.Index(list('abc')) 

203 Index(['a', 'b', 'c'], dtype='object') 

204 """

485 """ 

486 NOTE for new Index creation: 

487 

488 - _simple_new: It returns new Index with the same type as the caller. 

489 All metadata (such as name) must be provided by caller's responsibility. 

490 Using _shallow_copy is recommended because it fills these metadata 

491 otherwise specified. 

492 

493 - _shallow_copy: It returns new Index with the same type (using 

494 _simple_new), but fills caller's metadata otherwise specified. Passed 

495 kwargs will overwrite corresponding metadata. 

496 

497 - _shallow_copy_with_infer: It returns new Index inferring its type 

498 from passed values. It fills caller's metadata otherwise specified as the 

499 same as _shallow_copy. 

500 

501 See each method's docstring. 

502 """ 

503 

504 @classmethod 

505 def _simple_new(cls, values, name=None, dtype=None, **kwargs): 

506 """ 

507 We require that we have a dtype compat for the values. If we are passed 

508 a non-dtype compat, then coerce using the constructor. 

509 

510 Must be careful not to recurse. 

511 """ 

512 if not hasattr(values, 'dtype'): 

513 if (values is None or not len(values)) and dtype is not None: 

514 values = np.empty(0, dtype=dtype) 

515 else: 

516 values = np.array(values, copy=False) 

517 if is_object_dtype(values): 

518 values = cls(values, name=name, dtype=dtype, 

519 **kwargs)._ndarray_values 

520 

521 if isinstance(values, (ABCSeries, ABCIndexClass)): 

522 # Index._data must always be an ndarray. 

523 # This is no-copy for when _values is an ndarray, 

524 # which should be always at this point. 

525 values = np.asarray(values._values) 

526 

527 result = object.__new__(cls) 

528 result._data = values 

529 # _index_data is a (temporary?) fix to ensure that the direct data 

530 # manipulation we do in `_libs/reduction.pyx` continues to work. 

531 # We need access to the actual ndarray, since we're messing with 

532 # data buffers and strides. We don't re-use `_ndarray_values`, since 

533 # we actually set this value too. 

534 result._index_data = values 

535 result.name = name 

536 for k, v in compat.iteritems(kwargs): 

537 setattr(result, k, v) 

538 return result._reset_identity()

547 def _get_attributes_dict(self): 

548 """ 

549 Return an attributes dict for my class. 

550 """ 

551 return {k: getattr(self, k, None) for k in self._attributes}

553 _index_shared_docs['_shallow_copy'] = """ 

554 Create a new Index with the same class as the caller, don't copy the 

555 data, use the same object attributes with passed in attributes taking 

556 precedence. 

557 

558 *this is an internal non-public method* 

559 

560 Parameters 

561 ---------- 

562 values : the values to create the new Index, optional 

563 kwargs : updates the default attributes for this Index 

564 """ 

565 

566 @Appender(_index_shared_docs['_shallow_copy']) 

567 def _shallow_copy(self, values=None, **kwargs): 

568 if values is None: 

569 values = self.values 

570 attributes = self._get_attributes_dict() 

571 attributes.update(kwargs) 

572 if not len(values) and 'dtype' not in kwargs: 

573 attributes['dtype'] = self.dtype 

574 

575 # _simple_new expects an the type of self._data 

576 values = getattr(values, '_values', values) 

577 if isinstance(values, ABCDatetimeArray): 

578 # `self.values` returns `self` for tz-aware, so we need to unwrap 

579 # more specifically 

580 values = values.asi8 

581 

582 return self._simple_new(values, **attributes) 

583 

584 def _shallow_copy_with_infer(self, values, **kwargs): 

585 """ 

586 Create a new Index inferring the class with passed value, don't copy 

587 the data, use the same object attributes with passed in attributes 

588 taking precedence. 

589 

590 *this is an internal non-public method* 

591 

592 Parameters 

593 ---------- 

594 values : the values to create the new Index, optional 

595 kwargs : updates the default attributes for this Index 

596 """ 

597 attributes = self._get_attributes_dict() 

598 attributes.update(kwargs) 

599 attributes['copy'] = False 

600 if not len(values) and 'dtype' not in kwargs: 

601 attributes['dtype'] = self.dtype 

602 if self._infer_as_myclass: 

603 try: 

604 return self._constructor(values, **attributes) 

605 except (TypeError, ValueError): 

606 pass 

607 return Index(values, **attributes)

983 def format(self, name=False, formatter=None, **kwargs): 

984 """ 

985 Render a string representation of the Index.

987 header = [] 

988 if name: 

989 header.append(pprint_thing(self.name,

998 def _format_with_header(self, header, na_rep='NaN', **kwargs): 

999 values = self.values 

1000 

1001 from pandas.io.formats.format import format_array 

1002 

1003 if is_categorical_dtype(values.dtype): 

1004 values = np.array(values) 

1005 

1006 elif is_object_dtype(values.dtype): 

1007 values = lib.maybe_convert_objects(values, safe=1) 

1008 

1009 if is_object_dtype(values.dtype): 

1010 result = [pprint_thing(x, escape_chars=('\t', '\r', '\n')) 

1011 for x in values] 

1012 

1013 # could have nans 

1014 mask = isna(values) 

1015 if mask.any(): 

1016 result = np.array(result) 

1017 result[mask] = na_rep 

1018 result = result.tolist() 

1019 

1020 else: 

1021 result = _trim_front(format_array(values, None, justify='left')) 

1022 return header + result

1064 """

1076 if len(self) > 0:

1218 def _validate_names(self, name=None, names=None, deep=False): 

1219 """ 

1220 Handles the quirks of having a singular 'name' parameter for general 

1221 Index and plural 'names' parameter for MultiIndex. 

1222 """ 

1223 from copy import deepcopy 

1224 if names is not None and name is not None: 

1225 raise TypeError("Can only provide one of `names` and `name`") 

1226 elif names is None and name is None: 

1227 return deepcopy(self.names) if deep else self.names 

1228 elif names is not None: 

1229 if not is_list_like(names): 

1230 raise TypeError("Must pass list-like as `names`.") 

1231 return names 

1232 else: 

1233 if not is_list_like(name): 

1234 return [name] 

1235 return name

1237 def _get_names(self): 

1238 return FrozenList((self.name, ))

1240 def _set_names(self, values, level=None): 

1241 """ 

1242 Set new names on index. Each name has to be a hashable type. 

1243 

1244 Parameters 

1245 ---------- 

1246 values : str or sequence 

1247 name(s) to set 

1248 level : int, level name, or sequence of int/level names (default None) 

1249 If the index is a MultiIndex (hierarchical), level(s) to set (None 

1250 for all levels). Otherwise level must be None 

1251 

1252 Raises 

1253 ------ 

1254 TypeError if each name is not hashable. 

1255 """ 

1256 if not is_list_like(values): 

1257 raise ValueError('Names must be a list-like') 

1258 if len(values) != 1: 

1259 raise ValueError('Length of new names must be 1, got %d' % 

1260 len(values)) 

1261 

1262 # GH 20527 

1263 # All items in 'name' need to be hashable: 

1264 for name in values: 

1265 if not is_hashable(name): 

1266 raise TypeError('{}.name must be a hashable type' 

1267 .format(self.__class__.__name__)) 

1268 self.name = values[0] 

1269 

1270 names = property(fset=_set_names, fget=_get_names) 

1271 

1272 def set_names(self, names, level=None, inplace=False): 

1273 """ 

1274 Set Index or MultiIndex name. 

1275 

1276 Able to set new names partially and by level. 

1277 

1278 Parameters 

1279 ---------- 

1280 names : label or list of label 

1281 Name(s) to set. 

1282 level : int, label or list of int or label, optional 

1283 If the index is a MultiIndex, level(s) to set (None for all 

1284 levels). Otherwise level must be None. 

1285 inplace : bool, default False 

1286 Modifies the object directly, instead of creating a new Index or 

1287 MultiIndex. 

1288 

1289 Returns 

1290 ------- 

1291 Index 

1292 The same type as the caller or None if inplace is True. 

1293 

1294 See Also 

1295 -------- 

1296 Index.rename : Able to set new names without level. 

1297 

1298 Examples 

1299 -------- 

1300 >>> idx = pd.Index([1, 2, 3, 4]) 

1301 >>> idx 

1302 Int64Index([1, 2, 3, 4], dtype='int64') 

1303 >>> idx.set_names('quarter') 

1304 Int64Index([1, 2, 3, 4], dtype='int64', name='quarter') 

1305 

1306 >>> idx = pd.MultiIndex.from_product([['python', 'cobra'], 

1307 ... [2018, 2019]]) 

1308 >>> idx 

1309 MultiIndex(levels=[['cobra', 'python'], [2018, 2019]], 

1310 codes=[[1, 1, 0, 0], [0, 1, 0, 1]]) 

1311 >>> idx.set_names(['kind', 'year'], inplace=True) 

1312 >>> idx 

1313 MultiIndex(levels=[['cobra', 'python'], [2018, 2019]], 

1314 codes=[[1, 1, 0, 0], [0, 1, 0, 1]], 

1315 names=['kind', 'year']) 

1316 >>> idx.set_names('species', level=0) 

1317 MultiIndex(levels=[['cobra', 'python'], [2018, 2019]], 

1318 codes=[[1, 1, 0, 0], [0, 1, 0, 1]], 

1319 names=['species', 'year']) 

1320 """ 

1321 

1322 if level is not None and not isinstance(self, ABCMultiIndex): 

1323 raise ValueError('Level must be None for non-MultiIndex') 

1324 

1325 if level is not None and not is_list_like(level) and is_list_like( 

1326 names): 

1327 msg = "Names must be a string when a single level is provided." 

1328 raise TypeError(msg) 

1329 

1330 if not is_list_like(names) and level is None and self.nlevels > 1: 

1331 raise TypeError("Must pass list-like as `names`.") 

1332 

1333 if not is_list_like(names): 

1334 names = [names] 

1335 if level is not None and not is_list_like(level): 

1336 level = [level] 

1337 

1338 if inplace: 

1339 idx = self 

1340 else: 

1341 idx = self._shallow_copy() 

1342 idx._set_names(names, level=level) 

1343 if not inplace: 

1344 return idx

1406 def _validate_index_level(self, level): 

1407 """ 

1408 Validate index level. 

1409 

1410 For single-level Index getting level number is a no-op, but some 

1411 verification must be done like in MultiIndex. 

1412 

1413 """ 

1414 if isinstance(level, int): 

1415 if level < 0 and level != -1: 

1416 raise IndexError("Too many levels: Index has only 1 level," 

1417 " %d is not a valid level number" % (level, )) 

1418 elif level > 0: 

1419 raise IndexError("Too many levels:" 

1420 " Index has only 1 level, not %d" % 

1421 (level + 1)) 

1422 elif level != self.name: 

1423 raise KeyError('Level %s must be same as name (%s)' % 

1424 (level, self.name)) 

1425 

1426 def _get_level_number(self, level): 

1427 self._validate_index_level(level) 

1428 return 0

1491 def droplevel(self, level=0): 

1492 """ 

1493 Return index with requested level(s) removed. 

1494 

1495 If resulting index has only 1 level left, the result will be 

1496 of Index type, not MultiIndex. 

1497 

1498 .. versionadded:: 0.23.1 (support for non-MultiIndex) 

1499 

1500 Parameters 

1501 ---------- 

1502 level : int, str, or list-like, default 0 

1503 If a string is given, must be the name of a level 

1504 If list-like, elements must be names or indexes of levels. 

1505 

1506 Returns 

1507 ------- 

1508 index : Index or MultiIndex 

1509 """ 

1510 if not isinstance(level, (tuple, list)): 

1511 level = [level] 

1512 

1513 levnums = sorted(self._get_level_number(lev) for lev in level)[::-1] 

1514 

1515 if len(level) == 0: 

1516 return self 

1517 if len(level) >= self.nlevels: 

1518 raise ValueError("Cannot remove {} levels from an index with {} " 

1519 "levels: at least one level must be " 

1520 "left.".format(len(level), self.nlevels)) 

1521 # The two checks above guarantee that here self is a MultiIndex 

1522 

1523 new_levels = list(self.levels) 

1524 new_codes = list(self.codes) 

1525 new_names = list(self.names) 

1526 

1527 for i in levnums: 

1528 new_levels.pop(i) 

1529 new_codes.pop(i) 

1530 new_names.pop(i) 

1531 

1532 if len(new_levels) == 1: 

1533 

1534 # set nan if needed 

1535 mask = new_codes[0] == -1 

1536 result = new_levels[0].take(new_codes[0]) 

1537 if mask.any(): 

1538 result = result.putmask(mask, np.nan) 

1539 

1540 result.name = new_names[0] 

1541 return result 

1542 else: 

1543 from .multi import MultiIndex 

1544 return MultiIndex(levels=new_levels, codes=new_codes, 

1545 names=new_names, verify_integrity=False)

1553 Function mapping index values to groups

1750 def __setstate__(self, state): 

1751 """ 

1752 Necessary for making this object picklable. 

1753 """ 

1754 

1755 if isinstance(state, dict): 

1756 self._data = state.pop('data') 

1757 for k, v in compat.iteritems(state): 

1758 setattr(self, k, v) 

1759 

1760 elif isinstance(state, tuple): 

1761 

1762 if len(state) == 2: 

1763 nd_state, own_state = state 

1764 data = np.empty(nd_state[1], dtype=nd_state[2]) 

1765 np.ndarray.__setstate__(data, nd_state) 

1766 self.name = own_state[0] 

1767 

1768 else: # pragma: no cover 

1769 data = np.empty(state) 

1770 np.ndarray.__setstate__(data, state) 

1771 

1772 self._data = data 

1773 self._reset_identity() 

1774 else: 

1775 raise Exception("invalid pickle state")

1787 """ 

1788 Return if each value is NaN. 

1789 """ 

1790 if self._can_hold_na: 

1791 return isna(self) 

1792 else: 

1793 # shouldn't reach to this condition by checking hasnans beforehand 

1794 values = np.empty(len(self), dtype=np.bool_) 

1795 values.fill(False) 

1796 return values

1799 def _nan_idxs(self): 

1800 if self._can_hold_na: 

1801 w, = self._isnan.nonzero() 

1802 return w 

1803 else: 

1804 return np.array([], dtype=np.int64)

1808 """ 

1809 Return if I have any nans; enables various perf speedups. 

1810 """ 

1811 if self._can_hold_na: 

1812 return bool(self._isnan.any()) 

1813 else: 

1814 return False

1816 def isna(self): 

1817 """ 

1818 Detect missing values. 

1819 

1820 Return a boolean same-sized object indicating if the values are NA. 

1821 NA values, such as ``None``, :attr:`numpy.NaN` or :attr:`pd.NaT`, get 

1822 mapped to ``True`` values. 

1823 Everything else get mapped to ``False`` values. Characters such as 

1824 empty strings `''` or :attr:`numpy.inf` are not considered NA values 

1825 (unless you set ``pandas.options.mode.use_inf_as_na = True``). 

1826 

1827 .. versionadded:: 0.20.0 

1828 

1829 Returns 

1830 ------- 

1831 numpy.ndarray 

1832 A boolean array of whether my values are NA 

1833 

1834 See Also 

1835 -------- 

1836 pandas.Index.notna : Boolean inverse of isna. 

1837 pandas.Index.dropna : Omit entries with missing values. 

1838 pandas.isna : Top-level isna. 

1839 Series.isna : Detect missing values in Series object. 

1840 

1841 Examples 

1842 -------- 

1843 Show which entries in a pandas.Index are NA. The result is an 

1844 array. 

1845 

1846 >>> idx = pd.Index([5.2, 6.0, np.NaN]) 

1847 >>> idx 

1848 Float64Index([5.2, 6.0, nan], dtype='float64') 

1849 >>> idx.isna() 

1850 array([False, False, True], dtype=bool) 

1851 

1852 Empty strings are not considered NA values. None is considered an NA 

1853 value. 

1854 

1855 >>> idx = pd.Index(['black', '', 'red', None]) 

1856 >>> idx 

1857 Index(['black', '', 'red', None], dtype='object') 

1858 >>> idx.isna() 

1859 array([False, False, False, True], dtype=bool) 

1860 

1861 For datetimes, `NaT` (Not a Time) is considered as an NA value. 

1862 

1863 >>> idx = pd.DatetimeIndex([pd.Timestamp('1940-04-25'), 

1864 ... pd.Timestamp(''), None, pd.NaT]) 

1865 >>> idx 

1866 DatetimeIndex(['1940-04-25', 'NaT', 'NaT', 'NaT'], 

1867 dtype='datetime64[ns]', freq=None) 

1868 >>> idx.isna() 

1869 array([False, True, True, True], dtype=bool) 

1870 """ 

1871 return self._isnan 

1872 isnull = isna

2053 def duplicated(self, keep='first'): 

2054 """ 

2055 Indicate duplicate index values. 

2056 

2057 Duplicated values are indicated as ``True`` values in the resulting 

2058 array. Either all duplicates, all except the first, or all except the 

2059 last occurrence of duplicates can be indicated. 

2060 

2061 Parameters 

2062 ---------- 

2063 keep : {'first', 'last', False}, default 'first' 

2064 The value or values in a set of duplicates to mark as missing. 

2065 

2066 - 'first' : Mark duplicates as ``True`` except for the first 

2067 occurrence. 

2068 - 'last' : Mark duplicates as ``True`` except for the last 

2069 occurrence. 

2070 - ``False`` : Mark all duplicates as ``True``. 

2071 

2072 Returns 

2073 ------- 

2074 numpy.ndarray 

2075 

2076 See Also 

2077 -------- 

2078 pandas.Series.duplicated : Equivalent method on pandas.Series. 

2079 pandas.DataFrame.duplicated : Equivalent method on pandas.DataFrame. 

2080 pandas.Index.drop_duplicates : Remove duplicate values from Index. 

2081 

2082 Examples 

2083 -------- 

2084 By default, for each set of duplicated values, the first occurrence is 

2085 set to False and all others to True: 

2086 

2087 >>> idx = pd.Index(['lama', 'cow', 'lama', 'beetle', 'lama']) 

2088 >>> idx.duplicated() 

2089 array([False, False, True, False, True]) 

2090 

2091 which is equivalent to 

2092 

2093 >>> idx.duplicated(keep='first') 

2094 array([False, False, True, False, True]) 

2095 

2096 By using 'last', the last occurrence of each set of duplicated values 

2097 is set on False and all others on True: 

2098 

2099 >>> idx.duplicated(keep='last') 

2100 array([ True, False, True, False, False]) 

2101 

2102 By setting keep on ``False``, all duplicates are True: 

2103 

2104 >>> idx.duplicated(keep=False)

2510 def symmetric_difference(self, other, result_name=None, sort=None): 

2511 """ 

2512 Compute the symmetric difference of two Index objects. 

2513 

2514 Parameters 

2515 ---------- 

2516 other : Index or array-like 

2517 result_name : str 

2518 sort : False or None, default None 

2519 Whether to sort the resulting index. By default, the 

2520 values are attempted to be sorted, but any TypeError from 

2521 incomparable elements is caught by pandas. 

2522 

2523 * None : Attempt to sort the result, but catch any TypeErrors 

2524 from comparing incomparable elements. 

2525 * False : Do not sort the result. 

2526 

2527 .. versionadded:: 0.24.0 

2528 

2529 .. versionchanged:: 0.24.1 

2530 

2531 Changed the default value from ``True`` to ``None`` 

2532 (without change in behaviour). 

2533 

2534 Returns 

2535 ------- 

2536 symmetric_difference : Index 

2537 

2538 Notes 

2539 ----- 

2540 ``symmetric_difference`` contains elements that appear in either 

2541 ``idx1`` or ``idx2`` but not both. Equivalent to the Index created by 

2542 ``idx1.difference(idx2) | idx2.difference(idx1)`` with duplicates 

2543 dropped. 

2544 

2545 Examples 

2546 -------- 

2547 >>> idx1 = pd.Index([1, 2, 3, 4]) 

2548 >>> idx2 = pd.Index([2, 3, 4, 5]) 

2549 >>> idx1.symmetric_difference(idx2) 

2550 Int64Index([1, 5], dtype='int64') 

2551 

2552 You can also use the ``^`` operator: 

2553 

2554 >>> idx1 ^ idx2 

2555 Int64Index([1, 5], dtype='int64') 

2556 """ 

2557 self._validate_sort_keyword(sort) 

2558 self._assert_can_do_setop(other) 

2559 other, result_name_update = self._convert_can_do_setop(other) 

2560 if result_name is None: 

2561 result_name = result_name_update 

2562 

2563 this = self._get_unique_index() 

2564 other = other._get_unique_index() 

2565 indexer = this.get_indexer(other) 

2566 

2567 # {this} minus {other} 

2568 common_indexer = indexer.take((indexer != -1).nonzero()[0]) 

2569 left_indexer = np.setdiff1d(np.arange(this.size), common_indexer, 

2570 assume_unique=True) 

2571 left_diff = this.values.take(left_indexer) 

2572 

2573 # {other} minus {this} 

2574 right_indexer = (indexer == -1).nonzero()[0] 

2575 right_diff = other.values.take(right_indexer) 

2576 

2577 the_diff = _concat._concat_compat([left_diff, right_diff]) 

2578 if sort is None: 

2579 try: 

2580 the_diff = sorting.safe_sort(the_diff) 

2581 except TypeError: 

2582 pass 

2583 

2584 attribs = self._get_attributes_dict() 

2585 attribs['name'] = result_name 

2586 if 'freq' in attribs: 

2587 attribs['freq'] = None 

2588 return self._shallow_copy_with_infer(the_diff, **attribs)

2755 indexer = self._engine.get_indexer(target._ndarray_values) 

2756 

2757 return ensure_platform_int(indexer) 

2758 

2759 def _convert_tolerance(self, tolerance, target): 

2760 # override this method on subclasses 

2761 tolerance = np.asarray(tolerance) 

2762 if target.size != tolerance.size and tolerance.size > 1: 

2763 raise ValueError('list-like tolerance size must match ' 

2764 'target index size') 

2765 return tolerance

2767 def _get_fill_indexer(self, target, method, limit=None, tolerance=None): 

2768 if self.is_monotonic_increasing and target.is_monotonic_increasing: 

2769 method = (self._engine.get_pad_indexer if method == 'pad' else 

2770 self._engine.get_backfill_indexer) 

2771 indexer = method(target._ndarray_values, limit) 

2772 else: 

2773 indexer = self._get_fill_indexer_searchsorted(target, method, 

2774 limit) 

2775 if tolerance is not None: 

2776 indexer = self._filter_indexer_tolerance(target._ndarray_values, 

2777 indexer, 

2778 tolerance) 

2779 return indexer 

2780 

2781 def _get_fill_indexer_searchsorted(self, target, method, limit=None): 

2782 """ 

2783 Fallback pad/backfill get_indexer that works for monotonic decreasing 

2784 indexes and non-monotonic targets. 

2785 """ 

2786 if limit is not None: 

2787 raise ValueError('limit argument for %r method only well-defined ' 

2788 'if index and target are monotonic' % method) 

2789 

2790 side = 'left' if method == 'pad' else 'right' 

2791 

2792 # find exact matches first (this simplifies the algorithm) 

2793 indexer = self.get_indexer(target) 

2794 nonexact = (indexer == -1) 

2795 indexer[nonexact] = self._searchsorted_monotonic(target[nonexact], 

2796 side) 

2797 if side == 'left': 

2798 # searchsorted returns "indices into a sorted array such that, 

2799 # if the corresponding elements in v were inserted before the 

2800 # indices, the order of a would be preserved". 

2801 # Thus, we need to subtract 1 to find values to the left. 

2802 indexer[nonexact] -= 1 

2803 # This also mapped not found values (values of 0 from 

2804 # np.searchsorted) to -1, which conveniently is also our 

2805 # sentinel for missing values 

2806 else: 

2807 # Mark indices to the right of the largest value as not found 

2808 indexer[indexer == len(self)] = -1 

2809 return indexer 

2810 

2811 def _get_nearest_indexer(self, target, limit, tolerance): 

2812 """ 

2813 Get the indexer for the nearest index labels; requires an index with 

2814 values that can be subtracted from each other (e.g., not strings or 

2815 tuples). 

2816 """ 

2817 left_indexer = self.get_indexer(target, 'pad', limit=limit) 

2818 right_indexer = self.get_indexer(target, 'backfill', limit=limit) 

2819 

2820 target = np.asarray(target) 

2821 left_distances = abs(self.values[left_indexer] - target) 

2822 right_distances = abs(self.values[right_indexer] - target) 

2823 

2824 op = operator.lt if self.is_monotonic_increasing else operator.le 

2825 indexer = np.where(op(left_distances, right_distances) | 

2826 (right_indexer == -1), left_indexer, right_indexer) 

2827 if tolerance is not None: 

2828 indexer = self._filter_indexer_tolerance(target, indexer, 

2829 tolerance) 

2830 return indexer 

2831 

2832 def _filter_indexer_tolerance(self, target, indexer, tolerance): 

2833 distance = abs(self.values[indexer] - target) 

2834 indexer = np.where(distance <= tolerance, indexer, -1) 

2835 return indexer

3395 return_indexers=return_indexers)

3397 if flip_order: 

3398 if isinstance(result, tuple): 

3399 return result[0], result[2], result[1] 

3400 return result

3406 [other._ndarray_values], 

3407 how=how, 

3408 sort=True)

3424 def _join_level(self, other, level, how='left', return_indexers=False, 

3425 keep_order=True): 

3426 """ 

3427 The join method *only* affects the level of the resulting 

3428 MultiIndex. Otherwise it just exactly aligns the Index data to the 

3429 labels of the level in the MultiIndex. 

3430 

3431 If ```keep_order == True```, the order of the data indexed by the 

3432 MultiIndex will not be changed; otherwise, it will tie out 

3433 with `other`. 

3434 """ 

3435 from .multi import MultiIndex 

3436 

3437 def _get_leaf_sorter(labels): 

3438 """ 

3439 Returns sorter for the inner most level while preserving the 

3440 order of higher levels. 

3441 """ 

3442 if labels[0].size == 0: 

3443 return np.empty(0, dtype='int64') 

3444 

3445 if len(labels) == 1: 

3446 lab = ensure_int64(labels[0]) 

3447 sorter, _ = libalgos.groupsort_indexer(lab, 1 + lab.max()) 

3448 return sorter 

3449 

3450 # find indexers of beginning of each set of 

3451 # same-key labels w.r.t all but last level 

3452 tic = labels[0][:-1] != labels[0][1:] 

3453 for lab in labels[1:-1]: 

3454 tic |= lab[:-1] != lab[1:] 

3455 

3456 starts = np.hstack(([True], tic, [True])).nonzero()[0] 

3457 lab = ensure_int64(labels[-1]) 

3458 return lib.get_level_sorter(lab, ensure_int64(starts)) 

3459 

3460 if isinstance(self, MultiIndex) and isinstance(other, MultiIndex): 

3461 raise TypeError('Join on level between two MultiIndex objects ' 

3462 'is ambiguous') 

3463 

3464 left, right = self, other 

3465 

3466 flip_order = not isinstance(self, MultiIndex) 

3467 if flip_order: 

3468 left, right = right, left 

3469 how = {'right': 'left', 'left': 'right'}.get(how, how) 

3470 

3471 level = left._get_level_number(level) 

3472 old_level = left.levels[level] 

3473 

3474 if not right.is_unique: 

3475 raise NotImplementedError('Index._join_level on non-unique index ' 

3476 'is not implemented') 

3477 

3478 new_level, left_lev_indexer, right_lev_indexer = \ 

3479 old_level.join(right, how=how, return_indexers=True) 

3480 

3481 if left_lev_indexer is None: 

3482 if keep_order or len(left) == 0: 

3483 left_indexer = None 

3484 join_index = left 

3485 else: # sort the leaves 

3486 left_indexer = _get_leaf_sorter(left.codes[:level + 1]) 

3487 join_index = left[left_indexer] 

3488 

3489 else: 

3490 left_lev_indexer = ensure_int64(left_lev_indexer) 

3491 rev_indexer = lib.get_reverse_indexer(left_lev_indexer, 

3492 len(old_level)) 

3493 

3494 new_lev_codes = algos.take_nd(rev_indexer, left.codes[level], 

3495 allow_fill=False) 

3496 

3497 new_codes = list(left.codes) 

3498 new_codes[level] = new_lev_codes 

3499 

3500 new_levels = list(left.levels) 

3501 new_levels[level] = new_level 

3502 

3503 if keep_order: # just drop missing values. o.w. keep order 

3504 left_indexer = np.arange(len(left), dtype=np.intp) 

3505 mask = new_lev_codes != -1 

3506 if not mask.all(): 

3507 new_codes = [lab[mask] for lab in new_codes] 

3508 left_indexer = left_indexer[mask] 

3509 

3510 else: # tie out the order with other 

3511 if level == 0: # outer most level, take the fast route 

3512 ngroups = 1 + new_lev_codes.max() 

3513 left_indexer, counts = libalgos.groupsort_indexer( 

3514 new_lev_codes, ngroups) 

3515 

3516 # missing values are placed first; drop them! 

3517 left_indexer = left_indexer[counts[0]:] 

3518 new_codes = [lab[left_indexer] for lab in new_codes] 

3519 

3520 else: # sort the leaves 

3521 mask = new_lev_codes != -1 

3522 mask_all = mask.all() 

3523 if not mask_all: 

3524 new_codes = [lab[mask] for lab in new_codes] 

3525 

3526 left_indexer = _get_leaf_sorter(new_codes[:level + 1]) 

3527 new_codes = [lab[left_indexer] for lab in new_codes] 

3528 

3529 # left_indexers are w.r.t masked frame. 

3530 # reverse to original frame! 

3531 if not mask_all: 

3532 left_indexer = mask.nonzero()[0][left_indexer] 

3533 

3534 join_index = MultiIndex(levels=new_levels, codes=new_codes, 

3535 names=left.names, verify_integrity=False) 

3536 

3537 if right_lev_indexer is not None: 

3538 right_indexer = algos.take_nd(right_lev_indexer, 

3539 join_index.codes[level], 

3540 allow_fill=False) 

3541 else: 

3542 right_indexer = join_index.codes[level] 

3543 

3544 if flip_order: 

3545 left_indexer, right_indexer = right_indexer, left_indexer 

3546 

3547 if return_indexers: 

3548 left_indexer = (None if left_indexer is None 

3549 else ensure_platform_int(left_indexer)) 

3550 right_indexer = (None if right_indexer is None 

3551 else ensure_platform_int(right_indexer)) 

3552 return join_index, left_indexer, right_indexer 

3553 else: 

3554 return join_index

3556 def _join_monotonic(self, other, how='left', return_indexers=False): 

3557 if self.equals(other): 

3558 ret_index = other if how == 'right' else self 

3559 if return_indexers: 

3560 return ret_index, None, None 

3561 else: 

3562 return ret_index 

3563 

3564 sv = self._ndarray_values 

3565 ov = other._ndarray_values 

3566 

3567 if self.is_unique and other.is_unique: 

3568 # We can perform much better than the general case 

3569 if how == 'left': 

3570 join_index = self 

3571 lidx = None 

3572 ridx = self._left_indexer_unique(sv, ov) 

3573 elif how == 'right': 

3574 join_index = other 

3575 lidx = self._left_indexer_unique(ov, sv) 

3576 ridx = None 

3577 elif how == 'inner': 

3578 join_index, lidx, ridx = self._inner_indexer(sv, ov) 

3579 join_index = self._wrap_joined_index(join_index, other) 

3580 elif how == 'outer': 

3581 join_index, lidx, ridx = self._outer_indexer(sv, ov) 

3582 join_index = self._wrap_joined_index(join_index, other) 

3583 else: 

3584 if how == 'left': 

3585 join_index, lidx, ridx = self._left_indexer(sv, ov) 

3586 elif how == 'right': 

3587 join_index, ridx, lidx = self._left_indexer(ov, sv) 

3588 elif how == 'inner': 

3589 join_index, lidx, ridx = self._inner_indexer(sv, ov) 

3590 elif how == 'outer': 

3591 join_index, lidx, ridx = self._outer_indexer(sv, ov) 

3592 join_index = self._wrap_joined_index(join_index, other) 

3593 

3594 if return_indexers: 

3595 lidx = None if lidx is None else ensure_platform_int(lidx) 

3596 ridx = None if ridx is None else ensure_platform_int(ridx) 

3597 return join_index, lidx, ridx 

3598 else: 

3599 return join_index

4051 def equals(self, other): 

4052 """ 

4053 Determines if two Index objects contain the same elements. 

4054 """ 

4055 if self.is_(other): 

4056 return True 

4057 

4058 if not isinstance(other, Index):

4060 

4061 if is_object_dtype(self) and not is_object_dtype(other): 

4062 # if other is not object, use other's logic for coercion 

4063 return other.equals(self) 

4064 

4065 try: 

4066 return array_equivalent(com.values_from_object(self), 

4067 com.values_from_object(other)) 

4068 except Exception: 

4069 return False

4071 def identical(self, other): 

4072 """ 

4073 Similar to equals, but check that other comparable attributes are 

4074 also equal. 

4075 """ 

4076 return (self.equals(other) and 

4077 all((getattr(self, c, None) == getattr(other, c, None) 

4078 for c in self._comparables)) and 

4079 type(self) == type(other))

4081 def asof(self, label): 

4082 """ 

4083 Return the label from the index, or, if not present, the previous one. 

4084 

4085 Assuming that the index is sorted, return the passed index label if it 

4086 is in the index, or return the previous index label if the passed one 

4087 is not in the index. 

4088 

4089 Parameters 

4090 ---------- 

4091 label : object 

4092 The label up to which the method returns the latest index label. 

4093 

4094 Returns 

4095 ------- 

4096 object 

4097 The passed label if it is in the index. The previous label if the 

4098 passed label is not in the sorted index or `NaN` if there is no 

4099 such label. 

4100 

4101 See Also 

4102 -------- 

4103 Series.asof : Return the latest value in a Series up to the 

4104 passed index. 

4105 merge_asof : Perform an asof merge (similar to left join but it 

4106 matches on nearest key rather than equal key). 

4107 Index.get_loc : An `asof` is a thin wrapper around `get_loc` 

4108 with method='pad'. 

4109 

4110 Examples 

4111 -------- 

4112 `Index.asof` returns the latest index label up to the passed label. 

4113 

4114 >>> idx = pd.Index(['2013-12-31', '2014-01-02', '2014-01-03']) 

4115 >>> idx.asof('2014-01-01') 

4116 '2013-12-31' 

4117 

4118 If the label is in the index, the method returns the passed label. 

4119 

4120 >>> idx.asof('2014-01-02') 

4121 '2014-01-02' 

4122 

4123 If all of the labels in the index are later than the passed label, 

4124 NaN is returned. 

4125 

4126 >>> idx.asof('1999-01-02') 

4127 nan 

4128 

4129 If the index is not sorted, an error is raised. 

4130 

4131 >>> idx_not_sorted = pd.Index(['2013-12-31', '2015-01-02', 

4132 ... '2014-01-03']) 

4133 >>> idx_not_sorted.asof('2013-12-31') 

4134 Traceback (most recent call last): 

4135 ValueError: index must be monotonic increasing or decreasing 

4136 """ 

4137 try: 

4138 loc = self.get_loc(label, method='pad') 

4139 except KeyError: 

4140 return self._na_value 

4141 else: 

4142 if isinstance(loc, slice): 

4143 loc = loc.indices(len(self))[-1] 

4144 return self[loc]

4146 def asof_locs(self, where, mask): 

4147 """ 

4148 Finds the locations (indices) of the labels from the index for 

4149 every entry in the `where` argument. 

4150 

4151 As in the `asof` function, if the label (a particular entry in 

4152 `where`) is not in the index, the latest index label upto the 

4153 passed label is chosen and its index returned. 

4154 

4155 If all of the labels in the index are later than a label in `where`, 

4156 -1 is returned. 

4157 

4158 `mask` is used to ignore NA values in the index during calculation. 

4159 

4160 Parameters 

4161 ---------- 

4162 where : Index 

4163 An Index consisting of an array of timestamps. 

4164 mask : array-like 

4165 Array of booleans denoting where values in the original 

4166 data are not NA. 

4167 

4168 Returns 

4169 ------- 

4170 numpy.ndarray 

4171 An array of locations (indices) of the labels from the Index 

4172 which correspond to the return values of the `asof` function 

4173 for every element in `where`. 

4174 """ 

4175 locs = self.values[mask].searchsorted(where.values, side='right') 

4176 locs = np.where(locs > 0, locs - 1, 0) 

4177 

4178 result = np.arange(len(self))[mask].take(locs) 

4179 

4180 first = mask.argmax() 

4181 result[(locs == 0) & (where.values < self.values[first])] = -1 

4182 

4183 return result

4185 def sort_values(self, return_indexer=False, ascending=True): 

4186 """ 

4187 Return a sorted copy of the index. 

4188 

4189 Return a sorted copy of the index, and optionally return the indices 

4190 that sorted the index itself. 

4191 

4192 Parameters 

4193 ---------- 

4194 return_indexer : bool, default False 

4195 Should the indices that would sort the index be returned. 

4196 ascending : bool, default True 

4197 Should the index values be sorted in an ascending order. 

4198 

4199 Returns 

4200 ------- 

4201 sorted_index : pandas.Index 

4202 Sorted copy of the index. 

4203 indexer : numpy.ndarray, optional 

4204 The indices that the index itself was sorted by. 

4205 

4206 See Also 

4207 -------- 

4208 pandas.Series.sort_values : Sort values of a Series. 

4209 pandas.DataFrame.sort_values : Sort values in a DataFrame. 

4210 

4211 Examples 

4212 -------- 

4213 >>> idx = pd.Index([10, 100, 1, 1000]) 

4214 >>> idx 

4215 Int64Index([10, 100, 1, 1000], dtype='int64') 

4216 

4217 Sort values in ascending order (default behavior). 

4218 

4219 >>> idx.sort_values() 

4220 Int64Index([1, 10, 100, 1000], dtype='int64') 

4221 

4222 Sort values in descending order, and also get the indices `idx` was 

4223 sorted by. 

4224 

4225 >>> idx.sort_values(ascending=False, return_indexer=True) 

4226 (Int64Index([1000, 100, 10, 1], dtype='int64'), array([3, 1, 0, 2])) 

4227 """ 

4228 _as = self.argsort() 

4229 if not ascending: 

4230 _as = _as[::-1] 

4231 

4232 sorted_index = self.take(_as) 

4233 

4234 if return_indexer: 

4235 return sorted_index, _as 

4236 else: 

4237 return sorted_index

4342 def get_value(self, series, key): 

4343 """ 

4344 Fast lookup of value from 1-dimensional ndarray. Only use this if you 

4345 know what you're doing. 

4346 """ 

4347 

4348 # if we have something that is Index-like, then 

4349 # use this, e.g. DatetimeIndex 

4350 # Things like `Series._get_value` (via .at) pass the EA directly here. 

4351 s = getattr(series, '_values', series) 

4352 if isinstance(s, (ExtensionArray, Index)) and is_scalar(key): 

4353 # GH 20882, 21257 

4354 # Unify Index and ExtensionArray treatment 

4355 # First try to convert the key to a location 

4356 # If that fails, raise a KeyError if an integer 

4357 # index, otherwise, see if key is an integer, and 

4358 # try that 

4359 try: 

4360 iloc = self.get_loc(key) 

4361 return s[iloc] 

4362 except KeyError: 

4363 if (len(self) > 0 and 

4364 (self.holds_integer() or self.is_boolean())): 

4365 raise 

4366 elif is_integer(key): 

4367 return s[key] 

4368 

4369 s = com.values_from_object(series) 

4370 k = com.values_from_object(key) 

4371 

4372 k = self._convert_scalar_indexer(k, kind='getitem') 

4373 try: 

4374 return self._engine.get_value(s, k, 

4375 tz=getattr(series.dtype, 'tz', None)) 

4376 except KeyError as e1: 

4377 if len(self) > 0 and (self.holds_integer() or self.is_boolean()): 

4378 raise 

4379 

4380 try: 

4381 return libindex.get_value_box(s, key) 

4382 except IndexError: 

4383 raise 

4384 except TypeError: 

4385 # generator/iterator-like 

4386 if is_iterator(key): 

4387 raise InvalidIndexError(key) 

4388 else: 

4389 raise e1 

4390 except Exception: # pragma: no cover 

4391 raise e1 

4392 except TypeError: 

4393 # python 3 

4394 if is_scalar(key): # pragma: no cover 

4395 raise IndexError(key) 

4396 raise InvalidIndexError(key)

4405 """

4407 com.values_from_object(key), value)

4460 # A hack, but it works

4540 def isin(self, values, level=None): 

4541 """ 

4542 Return a boolean array where the index values are in `values`. 

4543 

4544 Compute boolean array of whether each index value is found in the 

4545 passed set of values. The length of the returned boolean array matches 

4546 the length of the index. 

4547 

4548 Parameters 

4549 ---------- 

4550 values : set or list-like 

4551 Sought values. 

4552 

4553 .. versionadded:: 0.18.1 

4554 

4555 Support for values as a set. 

4556 

4557 level : str or int, optional 

4558 Name or position of the index level to use (if the index is a 

4559 `MultiIndex`). 

4560 

4561 Returns 

4562 ------- 

4563 is_contained : ndarray 

4564 NumPy array of boolean values. 

4565 

4566 See Also 

4567 -------- 

4568 Series.isin : Same for Series. 

4569 DataFrame.isin : Same method for DataFrames. 

4570 

4571 Notes 

4572 ----- 

4573 In the case of `MultiIndex` you must either specify `values` as a 

4574 list-like object containing tuples that are the same length as the 

4575 number of levels, or specify `level`. Otherwise it will raise a 

4576 ``ValueError``. 

4577 

4578 If `level` is specified: 

4579 

4580 - if it is the name of one *and only one* index level, use that level; 

4581 - otherwise it should be a number indicating level position. 

4582 

4583 Examples 

4584 -------- 

4585 >>> idx = pd.Index([1,2,3]) 

4586 >>> idx 

4587 Int64Index([1, 2, 3], dtype='int64') 

4588 

4589 Check whether each index value in a list of values. 

4590 >>> idx.isin([1, 4]) 

4591 array([ True, False, False]) 

4592 

4593 >>> midx = pd.MultiIndex.from_arrays([[1,2,3], 

4594 ... ['red', 'blue', 'green']], 

4595 ... names=('number', 'color')) 

4596 >>> midx 

4597 MultiIndex(levels=[[1, 2, 3], ['blue', 'green', 'red']], 

4598 codes=[[0, 1, 2], [2, 0, 1]], 

4599 names=['number', 'color']) 

4600 

4601 Check whether the strings in the 'color' level of the MultiIndex 

4602 are in a list of colors. 

4603 

4604 >>> midx.isin(['red', 'orange', 'yellow'], level='color') 

4605 array([ True, False, False]) 

4606 

4607 To check across the levels of a MultiIndex, pass a list of tuples: 

4608 

4609 >>> midx.isin([(1, 'red'), (3, 'red')]) 

4610 array([ True, False, False]) 

4611 

4612 For a DatetimeIndex, string values in `values` are converted to 

4613 Timestamps. 

4614 

4615 >>> dates = ['2000-03-11', '2000-03-12', '2000-03-13'] 

4616 >>> dti = pd.to_datetime(dates) 

4617 >>> dti 

4618 DatetimeIndex(['2000-03-11', '2000-03-12', '2000-03-13'], 

4619 dtype='datetime64[ns]', freq=None) 

4620 

4621 >>> dti.isin(['2000-03-11']) 

4622 array([ True, False, False]) 

4623 """ 

4624 if level is not None: 

4625 self._validate_index_level(level) 

4626 return algos.isin(self, values)

4633 def slice_indexer(self, start=None, end=None, step=None, kind=None): 

4634 """ 

4635 For an ordered or unique index, compute the slice indexer for input 

4636 labels and step. 

4637 

4638 Parameters 

4639 ---------- 

4640 start : label, default None 

4641 If None, defaults to the beginning 

4642 end : label, default None 

4643 If None, defaults to the end 

4644 step : int, default None 

4645 kind : string, default None 

4646 

4647 Returns 

4648 ------- 

4649 indexer : slice 

4650 

4651 Raises 

4652 ------ 

4653 KeyError : If key does not exist, or key is not unique and index is 

4654 not ordered. 

4655 

4656 Notes 

4657 ----- 

4658 This function assumes that the data is sorted, so use at your own peril 

4659 

4660 Examples 

4661 --------- 

4662 This is a method on all index types. For example you can do: 

4663 

4664 >>> idx = pd.Index(list('abcd')) 

4665 >>> idx.slice_indexer(start='b', end='c') 

4666 slice(1, 3) 

4667 

4668 >>> idx = pd.MultiIndex.from_arrays([list('abcd'), list('efgh')]) 

4669 >>> idx.slice_indexer(start='b', end=('c', 'g'))

4672 start_slice, end_slice = self.slice_locs(start, end, step=step, 

4673 kind=kind)

4677 raise AssertionError("Start slice bound is non-scalar") 

4678 if not is_scalar(end_slice): 

4679 raise AssertionError("End slice bound is non-scalar") 

4680 

4681 return slice(start_slice, end_slice, step)

4744 self.is_floating())): 

4745 self._invalid_indexer('slice', label) 

4746 

4747 # we are trying to find integer bounds on a non-integer based index 

4748 # this is rejected (generally .loc gets you here) 

4749 elif is_integer(label): 

4750 self._invalid_indexer('slice', label) 

4751 

4752 return label 

4753 

4754 def _searchsorted_monotonic(self, label, side='left'): 

4755 if self.is_monotonic_increasing: 

4756 return self.searchsorted(label, side=side) 

4757 elif self.is_monotonic_decreasing: 

4758 # np.searchsorted expects ascending sort order, have to reverse 

4759 # everything for it to work (element ordering, search side and 

4760 # resulting value). 

4761 pos = self[::-1].searchsorted(label, side='right' if side == 'left' 

4762 else 'left') 

4763 return len(self) - pos 

4764 

4765 raise ValueError('index must be monotonic increasing or decreasing') 

4766 

4767 def _get_loc_only_exact_matches(self, key): 

4768 """ 

4769 This is overridden on subclasses (namely, IntervalIndex) to control 

4770 get_slice_bound. 

4771 """ 

4772 return self.get_loc(key) 

4773 

4774 def get_slice_bound(self, label, side, kind): 

4775 """ 

4776 Calculate slice bound that corresponds to given label. 

4777 

4778 Returns leftmost (one-past-the-rightmost if ``side=='right'``) position 

4779 of given label. 

4780 

4781 Parameters 

4782 ---------- 

4783 label : object 

4784 side : {'left', 'right'} 

4785 kind : {'ix', 'loc', 'getitem'} 

4786 """ 

4787 assert kind in ['ix', 'loc', 'getitem', None] 

4788 

4789 if side not in ('left', 'right'): 

4790 raise ValueError("Invalid value for side kwarg," 

4791 " must be either 'left' or 'right': %s" % 

4792 (side, )) 

4793 

4794 original_label = label 

4795 

4796 # For datetime indices label may be a string that has to be converted 

4797 # to datetime boundary according to its resolution. 

4798 label = self._maybe_cast_slice_bound(label, side, kind) 

4799 

4800 # we need to look up the label 

4801 try: 

4802 slc = self._get_loc_only_exact_matches(label) 

4803 except KeyError as err: 

4804 try: 

4805 return self._searchsorted_monotonic(label, side) 

4806 except ValueError: 

4807 # raise the original KeyError 

4808 raise err 

4809 

4810 if isinstance(slc, np.ndarray): 

4811 # get_loc may return a boolean array or an array of indices, which 

4812 # is OK as long as they are representable by a slice. 

4813 if is_bool_dtype(slc): 

4814 slc = lib.maybe_booleans_to_slice(slc.view('u1')) 

4815 else: 

4816 slc = lib.maybe_indices_to_slice(slc.astype('i8'), len(self)) 

4817 if isinstance(slc, np.ndarray): 

4818 raise KeyError("Cannot get %s slice bound for non-unique " 

4819 "label: %r" % (side, original_label)) 

4820 

4821 if isinstance(slc, slice): 

4822 if side == 'left': 

4823 return slc.start 

4824 else: 

4825 return slc.stop 

4826 else: 

4827 if side == 'right': 

4828 return slc + 1 

4829 else: 

4830 return slc 

4831 

4832 def slice_locs(self, start=None, end=None, step=None, kind=None): 

4833 """ 

4834 Compute slice locations for input labels. 

4835 

4836 Parameters 

4837 ---------- 

4838 start : label, default None 

4839 If None, defaults to the beginning 

4840 end : label, default None 

4841 If None, defaults to the end 

4842 step : int, defaults None 

4843 If None, defaults to 1 

4844 kind : {'ix', 'loc', 'getitem'} or None 

4845 

4846 Returns 

4847 ------- 

4848 start, end : int 

4849 

4850 See Also 

4851 -------- 

4852 Index.get_loc : Get location for a single label. 

4853 

4854 Notes 

4855 ----- 

4856 This method only works if the index is monotonic or unique. 

4857 

4858 Examples 

4859 --------- 

4860 >>> idx = pd.Index(list('abcd')) 

4861 >>> idx.slice_locs(start='b', end='c') 

4862 (1, 3) 

4863 """ 

4864 inc = (step is None or step >= 0) 

4865 

4866 if not inc: 

4867 # If it's a reverse slice, temporarily swap bounds. 

4868 start, end = end, start 

4869 

4870 start_slice = None 

4871 if start is not None: 

4872 start_slice = self.get_slice_bound(start, 'left', kind) 

4873 if start_slice is None: 

4874 start_slice = 0 

4875 

4876 end_slice = None 

4877 if end is not None: 

4878 end_slice = self.get_slice_bound(end, 'right', kind) 

4879 if end_slice is None: 

4880 end_slice = len(self) 

4881 

4882 if not inc: 

4883 # Bounds at this moment are swapped, swap them back and shift by 1. 

4884 # 

4885 # slice_locs('B', 'A', step=-1): s='B', e='A' 

4886 # 

4887 # s='A' e='B' 

4888 # AFTER SWAP: | | 

4889 # v ------------------> V 

4890 # ----------------------------------- 

4891 # | | |A|A|A|A| | | | | |B|B| | | | | 

4892 # ----------------------------------- 

4893 # ^ <------------------ ^ 

4894 # SHOULD BE: | | 

4895 # end=s-1 start=e-1 

4896 # 

4897 end_slice, start_slice = start_slice - 1, end_slice - 1 

4898 

4899 # i == -1 triggers ``len(self) + i`` selection that points to the 

4900 # last element, not before-the-first one, subtracting len(self) 

4901 # compensates that. 

4902 if end_slice == -1: 

4903 end_slice -= len(self) 

4904 if start_slice == -1: 

4905 start_slice -= len(self) 

4906 

4907 return start_slice, end_slice

4920 """

5059 def _validate_for_numeric_binop(self, other, op): 

5060 """ 

5061 Return valid other; evaluate or raise TypeError if we are not of 

5062 the appropriate type. 

5063 

5064 Notes 

5065 ----- 

5066 This is an internal method called by ops. 

5067 """ 

5068 opstr = '__{opname}__'.format(opname=op.__name__) 

5069 # if we are an inheritor of numeric, 

5070 # but not actually numeric (e.g. DatetimeIndex/PeriodIndex) 

5071 if not self._is_numeric_dtype: 

5072 raise TypeError("cannot evaluate a numeric op {opstr} " 

5073 "for type: {typ}" 

5074 .format(opstr=opstr, typ=type(self).__name__)) 

5075

5077 if not other._is_numeric_dtype: 

5078 raise TypeError("cannot evaluate a numeric op " 

5079 "{opstr} with type: {typ}" 

5080 .format(opstr=opstr, typ=type(other)))

5082 other = other.item() 

5083 

5084 if isinstance(other, (Index, ABCSeries, np.ndarray)): 

5085 if len(self) != len(other):

5087 "unequal lengths") 

5088 other = com.values_from_object(other) 

5089 if other.dtype.kind not in ['f', 'i', 'u']: 

5090 raise TypeError("cannot evaluate a numeric op " 

5091 "with a non-numeric dtype") 

5092 elif isinstance(other, (ABCDateOffset, np.timedelta64, timedelta)): 

5093 # higher up to handle 

5094 pass 

5095 elif isinstance(other, (datetime, np.datetime64)): 

5096 # higher up to handle 

5097 pass 

5098 else: 

5099 if not (is_float(other) or is_integer(other)): 

5100 raise TypeError("can only perform ops with scalar values") 

5101 

5102 return other

5325 An Index or other sequence

5393def _trim_front(strings): 

5394 """ 

5395 Trims zeros and decimal points. 

5396 """
